\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid15212217 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How long did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I should say about thirty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have any brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you tell me what order they were born in and how far about they were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 My sister was the first on the list. And her name was Constance Una Mary. She was about - six - about s
even years older than me. Well there was nothing to report about her really. Not at this juncture.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And there were younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, then - then a brother came next, Cecil Alfred Strong. He was about - two years - younger than my sister. And the
n came another - daughter, who died at a very early age, at about five months old. Then I'm the next one on the list. And - about another two years, and then a younger brother. And that completes our family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, I should say - twenty-three. About thirty-four, thirty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And by occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 By occupation he was a gentleman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 s outfitter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you know if he had any jobs before or after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He had a job before that - in Yorkshire - he was - there, and apprenticed to - an outfitters - establishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He remained an outfitter until he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He retired, he didn't die. Until he retired. Yes, that's right, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you have any idea how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 About - about the same age as my father, there was very little difference between them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you know if she worked before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you know what it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. She worked in - a gen - a gentleman's service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 She came from Enstone, in Oxfordshire, the same place that my father came from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 She obviously didn't go on working after she married at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I should like to ask you about your life at home when you were a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you tell me how many rooms there were in the house, can you remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Wait a minute. Seven. You want the name of the house? The house that - the - the name of the house was Bristol House. Bristol House.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did anybody else live in the house besides yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your mother pay anybody to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We had an aunt living with us. A sister of my mother's. She had a very smal
l she had money of her own - my mother used to recompense her a little. She had - she did - she didn't have a wage or anything like that, but they just used to give her a few pounds now and again. We had a maid - in the house - I think she - she might hav
e had a regular wage though what it would be, I - I don't remember, because - I was - I'm just trying to think, I don't remember what she had, she had a normal wage, a normal - servant's wage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did she live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, she came daily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember what she did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 She cleaned, yes, she - she cleaned and then we had another - charwoman in who did the laundry and part of the ironing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did she look after the children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We had a nurse girl to look after us, and she was calle
d Nellie Masters. She was a very nice girl, and she used to take us out, my brother and I you see. The others of course had grown up a bit. And - yes it was - her names was Nellie Master, I remember that very well, and I remember her, she was a very nice 
girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did you call her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Just called her Nellie. Just Nellie, yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did she live in Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. She lived in Woodstock and she lived round - what was known then as Back Lane which now has become Park - Lane. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The girl who came in to clean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The girl who came to clean, she lived in Woodstock. In Oxford Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And the charlady also lived in Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. The charlady lived in Old Woodstock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember what Nellie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We called her Nellie. We called her Nellie, then there was - the other girl was called Dorothy, and we called her Dorothy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember what she called you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 She called me Gwen. Yes. They all called me Gwen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And it was the same for your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, oh yes, they were all called by their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 hristian names.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did she call your mother, can you remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mrs Strong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How did you get on with Nellie, did you like her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh we loved her very much, yes, because on Sunday 
evenings - you see, my parents had gone to church and Nellie used to be - look after us and - we had a great big family bible, an enormous thing, with pictures in, pictorial one and it was marvellous, I remember I was terribly frightened, when we got to t
he page where the flood was, and all these poor people were hanging - onto branches and things you know and the lightning was coming out of the sky. That was very famous that book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was the washing done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 At home, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 It wasn't sent out at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, no, no washing was sent out, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your father and mother make or mend the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. I don't think my - my mother didn't make, but she always mended.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where were they bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 They came from, yes, shops in Woodstock and Oxford. Yes, we shopped in Woodstock and Oxford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have special trips to Oxford to buy clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes, we used to go in - well really when the clothes were needed more than special times to go, when we 
needed a new garment. If my mother could she always bought everything in Woodstock, but there were some things you couldn't get here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You didn't go in to St John's Fair or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes - not for shopping but we went to St G
iles Fair. And we adored the Woodstock fair, we saved up for that for a very very long time. And I think we were very proud to have collected up four ha'pennies.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 This would be the same with shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, they were bought, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your father mend the shoes himself at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. Did I omit to tell you that my father - kept gentlemen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 s - outfitting. Did I omit that? I told you that? Mm. Well they seem to come you see and one tells all you can about that and then you wonder if you've forgotten something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 If you think you've forgotten something do say so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, I will. Anything that might be of interest you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 None. My father was not a - housekeeper, he was - merely a shopkeeper. No, didn't believe in men working in the house. It's infra dig.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did he do any decorating or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Nothing, he didn't do a thing, no. No, we had to employ - everything. My father looked after his shop and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about with the children, did he dress or undress you or bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, nothing. Nothing at all except the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about when you went out, did your father take you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. He was very kind daddy was, when we were - when I was twelve, he took us to London, and we went to all - we went to all the place}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 s of interest. The zoo, Westmin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
ster Abbey, St Paul's Cathedral - the Tower of London - everywhere that was of any interest to children, that was part of our education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you stay in London that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, we had to go for the day. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was that without your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, mummy never came on those trips, no, my father considered he was - you know, the head of the house, and we'
d have to go and be initiated properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember anywhere else he took you like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes. Yes, we had a horse and trap. And we used to go out in this horse and trap and - I was very - thrilled to be allowed to hold the reins you know, j
ust to do a little - little bit you see. It was a real high trap, back and front, the children - we used to sit at the back sometimes and my father and - my mother would probably sit in the front - or we would - we - the bigger children sat in the front w
i
th my father. We were - we went - we used to have a daily trip - we had to stay - my uncle had a farm down in Gloucester - in Newent, and we used to go down there for our holidays, and to save the railway fare my father would take the horse and trap down,
 and then leave us there you see. It took perhaps the whole day to go to Gloucester, from Woodstock. Through Enstone you know and Chipping Norton, all the - regular -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your father ever look after you at all in the evening if your mother went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh no. Nothing to do with children, no. When my - yes, those - like those trips you see, or - if he took us to London that was a - a - a special do you see. Otherwise my father had - nothing to do with the children, when he came out of the shop, we wer
e supposed to be in bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have any sort of little jobs about the house you had to do regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh yes, yes. We had to - I had to clean the spoons - on Saturdays. I had to clean the spoons and my brother had to clean the knives. And - we had to do a little dusting, but nothing more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did each child have its own job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And your's was cleaning spoons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Cleaning spoons, and if there was any fruit to be peeled like apples or - any - anything like that, and at Chr
istmas time we had to - we had to stone the raisins, all those kind of things little children would love to do you know - we - yes, we were allowed to do all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
long did you go on doing these, after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no. Oh no. Not when
 I left school, no, I didn't do anything at all. I went - I went away you see, when I left school, I went to Oxford to school, and when I left school I went away to Camberley, and I was one of the first lady clerks in the bank. Yes. And I went into the Lo
ndon and Provincial Bank, which - was taken over by - Barclays. It became Barclays. The amalgamation with Barclays you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember any of the special jobs that your brothers and sisters had to do, did they have special jobs each to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes. Well - we took over, you see, they did our jobs, until we were grown up enough to take over from them, when they were considered too big to do that, then - my brother went away to boarding school you see and my sister would - went away and - and she
 was apprenticed to millinery, she learned the millinery trade. Making hats in other words.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So the older ones helped the younger ones with their jobs and things they found difficult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, though we didn't - I mean the girl who came to look after
 us did everything like that. And I couldn't tell you - I've forgotten now whether we had Nellie - I think Nellie must have been one of the - pillars of the - of the - of the place. She seemed to have been with us years. But you see I was much younger tha
n my sister, and what happened when she was my age I - I don't know you see. Can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So you can't remember your sister helping you get dressed or teaching you to do up - your boots, or did Nellie do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, no, I think my sister must ha
ve helped, or - or one of the girls in the house. We had a girl, a maid called Dorothy, she - I - I think she would have helped us in those sort of ways. 'Course it's a - very long time ago, none's mind might be a little faltery. I'm vouching - I'm vouchi
n
g for the truth, what I'm telling you - is the truth. Is all this going down here? Can you cut some of it out if it's - it's - if it's superfluous? Yes. Oh yes. Oh that's all right then. Anything that I've said that's ridiculous. I'm trying to help you to
 be of interest. Something interesting you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Very definitely. As far as I can remember back we had to go to bed - at - half past six, in the winter, and seven o'clock in the summer. And my father expected us to be in bed when he came out of the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your mother put you to bed or one of the girls in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well I think - I think - my - well I - I can't quite remember right back - but I think my mother would ha
ve seen us to bed. And then my auntie who was living with us - Miss Clarey, she - helped us a lot, in little things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What age did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh I should say - from the time I was eight, I should think, about that anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you share the bedroom or the bed with somebody or did you have your own rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. My brother had - what we called the spare room, and I slept in the same room that my auntie shared. We didn't share the same bed but we had the same room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about the other brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well, you see, when - from the time I can remember they'd gone away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Except for the younger one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, except for Arthur. And Arthur - slept in the other room, in the spare room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have a bath in the house or did you have a special room where you had baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We had a bathroom, but until we were big enough - to go up into the bathroom, we had one of those }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 inc baths - on the kitchen floor, and Nellie used to see that we were - fairly abluted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember how often you were thoroughly abluted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well, we were thoroughly abluted - I think on Saturdays. It was once a week in those days, and tho - thoroughly abluted in the morning, but not immersed, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How often did you have clean clothes put on, would that be on a Saturday as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, yes, clean, the clean clothes were once a week. Unless anything unforeseen happened you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where did the family have their meals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We had - we had - breakfast and lunch - in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they eat in any other room at any other time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes. Yes, we - we used to have - oh very often - on Saturdays we had tea in the kitchen. But other days we had meals in the dining room. And we - my father was the organis
t at the Methodist church, a voluntary organist, and on Sunday - we always had meals in the dining room, you know all sort of proper, and - especially when we entertained the minister. We entertained the minister in our turn. We were Methodists you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And different chapel families took it in turn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Took it in turn to entertain the ministers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Would this be Sunday lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Just - just on Sunday, for Sunday lunch and tea. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Cooked in the kitchen, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember what she cooked on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, a stove. I can see it now, a little stove with a fire here and a little tuck there, and a little boiler down there that heated the hot water, came out of this little tap. And one oven, one nice big oven at the side. That did all the cooking you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When was breakfast eaten, what sort of time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We had breakfast usually at eight o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were all the family there at breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Those that were at home. Of course the others as I told you had gone away, my brother, my elder brother and sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember what sort of things you had for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We had porridge. And we had golden syrup on it. And that was followed by - either brown or white bread any butter a
nd toast. We - we had toast on special days, not every day. We had bread and butter, and marmalade, and - I was just trying to think, no, we didn't have fruit at breakfast. I thought perhaps we did have fruit but I don't think we did, no, it was just brea
d and butter, and on high days we had toast.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What was a high day, would that be Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes, mainly Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have anything else special on Sunday at all, would you have an egg?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, oh yes, we had - it was - it was alwa
ys special on Sundays. And - me - there was no cooking done on Sundays in our house. We - no, no cooking was allowed to be done on Sundays. We had a cold lunch. My father was a Methodist and he said it wasn't necessary to cook on the Sabbath, the Lord wou
l
d take care of those who had cold food on the Sabbath. So we - we didn't eat, we - we had hot food sometimes on the Sabbath, but it was always heated up when we got back. There - no one stayed - away from church to cook on Sundays. And I think the porridg
e
, if I remember rightly, was made on Saturday night. And - and just heated on - on Sunday. And all the shoes were cleaned, we had a yard boy, and the yard boy had to clean all the shoes - all put out and they were all beautifully cleaned, all laid in pair
s, I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was done on a Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was done on the Saturday, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did somebody come in to heat up the food while you were at chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, no, no, it was heated up when we got back. Unless - I mummy may ha
ve a put a joint in the - if we were going to have it warm but very seldom did we have anything hot, it was always cold, but - so just supposing it was going to be hot, she would make the oven so that it would just heat the meat while we'd gone away. It w
as only an hour you see in church on Sunday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But you sometimes had a warm breakfast on a Sunday, an egg or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I think we had an egg occasionally. But of course an egg was a holiday. We always had marmalade and - whether 
we had toast, I can't remember about Sunday toast. I believe we had toast on Sundays. You know it's a heck of a long time to go back isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your parents have the same sort of things for breakfast?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes, they didn't have - never had anything different from us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember what time you had lunch or midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Lunch. Lunch on - on - Lunch on Sunday was directly we came out of church, we were supposed to come out at twelve and it was mainly twelve o'clock. And on weekdays we always had lunch at twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And all the family would be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Those that were at home, yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you remember what you had to eat and drink at midday meal again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, well some days we had soup to start o
ff. And then we nearly always had cooked meat, and - two vegetables, and then we had a sweet, a tart or - a steamed pudding, all - but my - my - my auntie did the cooking mostly. And it was varied you see. We had a very varied - very nice diet. All the me
ats that you can get now, well - some you can't get now that we used to have you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about the evening meal, you had afternoon tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. We always had a very good tea, about half past four, we had our tea. That was a very good meal, a tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was that all the family or just the children and mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Daddy was generally for - with us for tea. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He came back from the shop to have tea with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well the shop was - at the side of the house. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And that would be about half past four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, about half past four we had tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember what sort of thing you had for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, well we had bread and butter, mainly white bread and butter on weekdays and brown and white on Sunday, and - we had - sometime
s little cake - oh, and then we had jam, always one or two jams that my mother had made a choice of jam you see, and - then we had cakes, and - and just tea, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was Sunday tea very special?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 A very - yes, generally - a sponge sandwich
 for tea. You know, a nice flat one. And sometimes little cakes with that on Sunday. It was always - everything was a little better on the Lord's day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about dinner, or late evening meal, did the children have that or did your parents have any meal after tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, it was always supper. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 Supper - supper sometimes - ham}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  or - cold meat. That sort - of course this is when we were growing up, we weren't - didn't have any meat when we were children. We had bread and milk. And - things like that you s
ee. Soft - foods to go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What time would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well when we - in these days we went to bed about - seven o'clock. Seven o'clock, half past seven in the summer, so half past seven to eight, and I remember the Salvation Army - used to - s
tand round - we had a big lamp outside our bedroom window, because we looked out into Oxford Street, and the Salvation Army used to come - in - well sometimes in the winter and in the summer, and oh it was a highlight of the Salvation Army were there, of 
c
ourse we used to go up and open the window you see and throw them a penny or ha'penny or whatever we'd got down. And - you - your - your still asking me about supper, well I don't think supper was a very - it wasn't a sit down proper meal, supper. Sometim
es we would have - have it on a plate round the fire. And the - nearly always we had cocoa. We had a choice of coffee or cocoa - or sometimes Bournevita for supper. But never tea at suppertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your parents have this with you or did they have their cold meat at some other time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No, they - they had their supper later. We always had our supper first. And we had to be in bed when my father came out of the shop. By the way, I must tell you this 'cos this is very interesting. We - my father used to
 - he - he was a very very good man in his way, he used to play games with us. This was - when he came out of the shop you see, between that and our bedtime, we had a full size bagatelle board, and we loved that, we used to bring that and he taught us how
 to play chess, and draughts, and Helma and Ludo, tiddly-winks, snakes and ladders, all the games the children had, we - I should think we had ever game in our house. My father believe in plenty of recreation. Knew all the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did she make jam or bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Mm. Not vegetables. We used to bottle fruit and - we made practically all our own jams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your mother did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 My aunt. Did that. Yes, my aunt did all the cooking, except cakes, and my mother always made the cakes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did she make pickles or wine or medicine, anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We made elderberry wine, but we didn't make any - pickles. Oh, pickled onions and pickled cabbage I believe they did do that, y
es, I remember they did. My aunt, yes, my aunt did those. My aunt did all the cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they grew vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, in the garden we had - we had - not a very large garden, the only - fruit we had in the garden we had a cherry tree in
 the middle of the lawn, and we had a pear tree, and a fig tree. But no other fruit in the garden at all. It was a small - it was a small sort of - in the middle of the - town garden you know with wall-all the way round. We had a horse and cart. Horse and
 trap rather. Until we - until my father bought the first motor car. And the horse was kept in the stable, we always kept a stable boy. And the stable boy cleaned the shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So they bought their fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they buy tinned or dried fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Sometimes tinned fruits, we bought - well mostly mummy bought tinned fruits, as well as the other fruits, but - we - they used to make jam, I remember - a big - great big pot we had on the - stove, with jam fizzling up in it you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That would be fruit that your mother would buy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
That - yes, that she bought, yes. Well I think my father - you see he had a country round. He used to go round - the villages and so on - with the - with this - thi
s clothing and so on, and - daddy was often in the way of getting - fruit you see, perhaps we'll buy a dozen pounds of plums or something then my mother would make that into jam.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you keep any livestock at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Now - do you want to en -
 me to enumerate them all? Well we had snakes, in a glass case. We had goldfish. We had - a kitten, a tortoise - a rabbit, rabbits, in a hutch, and a dog, and a horse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you keep anything like hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, ours wasn't big enough. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How many times a week did you eat meat, did you eat meat every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have any tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, but that was mostly for supper like - we would have that - what is now called Unox, that kind of thing, and sardines, those sort of 
things you know. But we had mostly fresh meat at lunch every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you ever remember seeing your mother having less food than the rest of the family so that you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, we had plenty of food. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, unless we got silly and then we were reprimanded but - we were - it was a very - nice homely atmosphere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Whatever was on the table we could, but we were never allowed to ask for things that weren't on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You didn't have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, no. Oh no, my parents - and if we didn't like one thing, it didn't matter, we could have something else that was on the table.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was it all right to leave food on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, we had to eat everything. If we asked for it we must eat it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt, could you ask someone to pass it to your or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, we could ask for it to be passed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. We could have second helping of anything, but we had to eat it. If we'd asked for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, we were supposed to sit up properly to the table, but we were always taught to handle our knife and fork correctly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you ever bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. And we always said grace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
We had to wait 'til the - well, we - we had to ask to get down, if some of the others hadn't finished, supposing we were going out somewhere, daddy wasn't all that bad you know, he'd say, well, oh yes, of cou
rse you can go, yes. But we had to ask to get down, if we wanted to leave the table before - we were all ready.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did all the family sit at the same table for the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Even when you were quite small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No. No. We - you see, we had breakfast in the kitchen, and - lunch - in the kitchen. Except on Sundays. On Sundays the - table was all laid up - oh you've no idea what it was like. Oh all the best cutlery and ev
erything came out on Sundays, huge great cruets, silver things you know and all - oh it - Sundays was areal - it was the Lord's day, and we had to give to him the best. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How was the meal served and who served it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 My father always - carved t
he meat, and my mother always served the vegetables. And then if there were sauces well - sometimes my auntie would serve the sauce, or we could help ourselves. When we got bigger you know. Until we were big we were always given, you know, the thing - eve
rything, given everything, until we were old enough to - help ourselves, and then we were - they were very good and kind you know, and - and indulgent in a way - if we didn't go too far.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you served in a special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, not special - no, the ones who came - and asked first - were served first. There was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your father would just carve the meat and pass it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, would pass it round. Mm. hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where did the younger brother, before he could feed himself, did he eat with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well he had - yes, he had a high chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Who fed him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You said you had some servants who came in during the day, did they eat with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. They - ate in the house after we'd finished. Yes. Mm h.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they eat -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The same food, exactly. They were given the same food and plenty of it, and - but they always ate after us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 They'd eat in the kitchen just after you'd finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 They didn't have a separate room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, no, no, they ate after we'd finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your aunt eat with the servants or eat with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, she ate with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 This is about things like discipline and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, oh yes, that comes into it doesn't it, by jove, there was plenty of it I can tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember what - was your mother sort of person you could talk to easily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Lovely my mother. My mother was one of the loveliest people you've ever met in your life. And - if she'd seen 
you - you would have felt now this lady loves everybody, and she did. She was beautiful my mother. Beautiful, and so was my auntie. But daddy was a bit stern you know and a bit strict. We were - honestly to be truthful we were a bit afraid of my father. A
nd we had to call him father and not dad or daddy. Well sometimes - when I grew - was growing up I called him daddy and he didn't seem to object, I think he thought I'd begun to like him a bit. Oh dear. I didn't like him at one time, he was too strict.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your mother show you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes. We used to often feign toothache to be - put here you know and rocked like this you know. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And if you had worries as a child you felt you could talk to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh to mummy, we never told daddy anything. Oh no, no, don't tell him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So your father then was quite different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He wasn't easy to talk to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, no, no, no. No. And yet he was kind you know. He had a nice kind soft side. But he was - he was very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 stern}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  - i
f we'd done wrong, anything wrong, oh dear oh dear. We had to go to bed - early if we'd done anything really bad. But never without any supper. We always had our meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you know how your parents expected you to behaved towards them, did they expect you to show respect in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well, general. It was general. I mean we - we - we - we never answered my father back ever, in my life. If he were in here now I wouldn't dare to answer him back. Or
 to argue with him. No, his word was law. Now my mother you see, we could get round her. She was tender you know. And - if - ever - we asked my father for anything and he wasn't quite sure, he'd say, well I don't know, you go and ask your mother. So we we
nt and asked my mother. But if - we'd asked my mother first, and she said, well you go and ask your father, we never asked him. I'm letting you into lots of household secrets you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well they'll remain secrets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, I'm sure, yes. I can imagine you feeling very amused.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember if your parents as it were brought you up to behave in certain ways to your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well, no. No. We were a one family and - there were little squabbles between the children from time to 
time you see, and perhaps one would hit the other or something but - I - my parents never entered into that. And my father really - was a businessman, when he was out of his business - he wanted to be quiet, he read a lot, he was a big reader. A vulture f
o
r books my father. My mother - well - liked - and yet he liked to play games with us, but there was always a kind of restriction - on my father and all his movements and everything about him. My mother you could have told her anything, if you'd murdered s
omebody - you'd go and tell your mother, and my mother would understand. She'd say, well I'm sure they deserved it or did something, you know, she'd always take our part. She was very very soft, my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 If another child hit you would your parents expect you to hit it back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We would never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 tell them about it. We probably would have hit them back. If they'd - if they'd hit us or hurt us, we would hurt them back, oh we never told my parents anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So you've no idea how they felt about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh no. No idea at all. But - my father - would say - from a Christian angle, and it was always a Christian angle with daddy, he was a good man, though he was a little hard, but he was really good, he would - he would have said, well 
the bible says - you must turn the other cheek, so you must not hit anybody back. I'm sure that would have been his attitude. And - and mummy, from a different angle, she would have said, oh well I shouldn't hit them back, you know. She was a soft - ever 
so soft. He was a little hard you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Christians. That was the one outlook. My father said, I don't mind what you do in life, I don't mind what position you have in lif
e, I'm not - I'm very interested for you to bet on and do well, but that's not the most important thing. But I want you all to love the Lord, and serve him. That's my dearest wish and I'm sure it was. He was a holy man, my father. He really was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I suppose your father and your mother would think that swearing was very bad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh - oh we never dared. We didn't know any words. We never heard it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about in other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What, my parents? Oh my father would say, you mustn't have anything to do with those people. Mustn't mix with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When your parents were talking, if they were talking between themselves, were you allowed to join in as children or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You had to sit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Be seen and not heard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 If you did do something wrong that your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well, my father might say, well - you must be punished for this because you know it's wrong, you knew when you did it it was wrong, and - you must go to bed. You must go to bed earl
y. For so many days or so - you know, a week or so. And - and - and if it was very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 bad then we would be perhaps de}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
prived of something that we liked very much, that the others were having, we weren't allowed to have it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 A special sort of sweet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, yes, anything like that, sweets or - or particular sort of food. If - if - if he knew we were very fond of something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your father always did the punishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, my mother never could punish us. She hadn
't got the heart to punish anybody or anything. She was the sweetest thing. Oh my mother was beautiful, you'd have loved her. You would really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did this seem to happen a lot when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, we didn't get into many scrapes you know. N
o. You see, the two older ones - well I mean they were away from us, now the brother that's living over at Milverton in New Road, that brother and I were - similar ages you see, he used to tease me a lot and - that sort of thing, but - but we didn't - you
 
see, the big ones and the little ones didn't mix - very much at all, you see my brother was away at boarding school, my sister was away learning millinery, and we didn't see them. There's such a tremendous disparagement of age - between us. The little sis
ter that was in the middle of us all, died. She was only five months old when she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, I remember I had to go to bed. That was our punishment. We weren't thrashed or hit about. We had to go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember what it was for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes I can remember, because I went to bed - I had a - took a boat out on Blenheim Lake with - this man's - brother, older brother, this man next door, he's older brother, and another fellow,
 took - we two girls and a friend and myself out on the lake in a rowing boat, and I'd forgotten it was my music lesson. And my music master had come all the way from Wootten, which is a place two or three miles out here, and he'd come over and of course 
m
y father had to pay for the lesson, and I wasn't here. And when I came home my father just looked at me and - from his look I knew I'd done something, and he said, where have you been? I said, I've been out - in the park daddy. Who have you been with? I s
a
id, well we've been with Wallace Mayes, and Jockey Londworth. And he said, well don't you remember it's your music lesson? And Mr Luft has come all the way from Wootton to give you that lesson, now he said you go to bed. And I had to go to bed. I was quit
e big.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh about fourteen. Thirteen, fourteen, and of course that was a very young age in those days compared with what it is now. I mean at fifteen now they want to be married don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Or did one parent play a more important part than the other do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Both - Both. My mother very - very courteously and kindly, my father - rather - sternly. T
here was a great difference in the characters of both - father and mother. I don't want you to think my father was a cruel man, he wasn't, but he was very stern and very - just so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 -Oh yes, quite different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You got presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh yes, presents - and special things for tea, always on a birthday. And we were generally allowed to stay up a bit later at night - when we got a birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, we had a party. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember what the parties were like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well the parties were lovely, we played all children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 s games you know, and - of course we had our own age groups, my young brother and I you see, we had a joint party. His birthday 
was in December and mine was in February, and we had a joint party. It didn't matter, sometimes it was on his birthday, and then it was - another time it was on my birthday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember about Christmas Day and what you did with your father and mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh it was - oh yes, we had a lovely Christmas Day. We had - our presents - were all - we had a very big dining room and a very long table, and our presents first of all when we were very small, until we got artful, our presents were always put
 under the bed, father Christmas came down the chimney, which we hadn't got incidentally, he came down the chimney and he put them under the bed. Well then we got to having - when we got a bit bigger you see we were artful, and we used to wait until they'
d
 been and put the presents, and then we used to get out of bed and we used to eat all our sugar mice, and be ill you see, we couldn't eat any meals at Christmas. So they vetoed that, and we had to have our presents in the dining room, the big dining room 
w
ith a great big table. And the - the - young - the youngest children opened their presents first. And of course we - none of us knew that - that - we - we really thought it was Father Christmas when we were very small, and that - that my mother and father
 
hadn't seen the presents and of course we were - hours and hours showing them all the things that we got. They were very very generous - at Christmas, we had lovely books and toys and - excuse me, games you know. Oh it was a very happy time. We always wen
t
 to church on Christmas morning. My father played the organ, then in the afternoon we came home, and we had - we used to play games or daddy would read a story to us - and then we would have our Christmas tea with a Christmas cake, a nice big cake you kno
w, and - then in the evening we would generally end up with playing bagatelle. That was our Christmas Day, but we always went to church in the morning. That was absolutely marvellous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, we h
ad a beautiful piano. And a violin. My father used to scrape away on the violin, and - of course I used to - I was taught the piano, as you will remember, when I went on the lake. And - we - what else, oh we played games, yes, we had a lovely lot of games
.
 And daddy would play games with us. He was very good. But no games on Sundays. I played the piano, my brother - my elder brother played the violin, and - we didn't have anything like - not those things, they weren't in vogue in those days at all, I don't
 think they were ever heard of - banjo, yes, I think a banjo was but not these other - funny things. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was there anybody in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, I sang. Never heard such a row in your life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you get together in the evenings and make music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh yes, on Sun - on Sundays. My father had a little American organ, and it stood there, I can see it now, dear little American organ, and my father used to play hymns and we used to invite people in on Sunday evening, and sing hymns, on Sundays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 People from chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And other tradesmen in the town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Anybody. Yes. Girls at the - girls at work - engaged in serving in the shops, you know, if they came to church - they could come into the house, and mummy alw
ays made coffee for them on Sunday evenings you know. Yes, there was the - little American organ, but we weren't allowed to sing anything but hymns on Sunday. Nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you sing at any other time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. And I belonged to a concert part
y, and we used to go out in a - in a - well it was - it was like a great big - farm - cart, and two horses. We used to go round the country, we called - whatever was it we called ourselves? A singing gro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15757918\charrsid15815407 up we had, a sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 pirouette}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  group, you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was - a bit later - in life. When I was growing up, say when I was about - thirteen and fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was that to do with the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, that was a - a - a group in - organised in the village - in the town. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Plenty. Oceans of books. My father was a vulture for reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember what sort of books they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, daddy loved travel books. And you see my father went to Palestine and - and Egypt and - all - o
h all the way round - he had his photograph taken in Jerusalem on Christmas Day. Yes. And - oh he - yes, he went - he was away six weeks, and that was a long time you know, when we were little children, and my mother and father, they had a code, so that w
hen they sent - a - well what we would call a telegram, I've forgotten what they called it in those days - had a different name.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Cablegram?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, sort of a cable thing you know, sort of say brilliant you see, well then - underneath, she would got
 - she would have got what that meant, what that one word meant, the children all very well and w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
re very happy, we hope you're having a good time you see. Oh yes, he went all the way round, went to Turkey and - oh - he - he was away six weeks, so you can 
tell it was - quite a tour. And he was the first man out of Woodstock to go to Palestine, when he came back you should have seen the people, coming round the front door to see all the trophies he brought back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember newspapers and which ones they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Always the Daily News. No Sunday papers. Sunday paper never darkened our door. We had the Daily News. And - I think that was the only paper we ever had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have any magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I - besides booklets and things, but they wer
e all missionary ones. We didn't have - there weren't such things really in those days like there are today you know, I mean there's too much literature today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But you had the missionary magazines, no others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. No. No, we didn't, I don't r
emember - I think though daddy did have a book - was there one called the Conquest? Or was - what - what - what was the literature in those days? Well you can't remember can you? I can't - no, and I can't remember. We had plenty of missionary and plenty o
f biblical, you know, plenty of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 hristian literature always in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your mother read as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. But not very much, she wasn't a reader like my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they ever read aloud to you or to one another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Daddy did, yes, he w
as very good, he'd read stories to us. And - I know my father always bought every Christmas for my brother, my little brother, a Chatterbox. It was a big book with page - stories and - and - and pictures. He had a Chatterbox. And I had - a big book called
 Sunday at Home. That was mine. And his was Chatterbox. And they were really very good books. Nice stories for children you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you ever remember any funerals in the family, and what they were like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, I remember when my grandfather di
ed, and of course all the family came - into the sitting room you see, the aunts came from - round about you see and my father took them all you see, to - and I remember I said - I thought it was a very solemn occasion when my grandfather died, oh I thoug
h
t it was very very sad and I said to them all as they were going out of the front door, I said, well now, I said, don't forget now, remember Nellie. Nellie was there. And I - I looked at Nellie and I said, oh dear, and I said, oh dear, and then as they we
r
e going out of the front door, I said, well now - now you're going - don't forget all of you, you're going to a funeral, don't forget you have to cry. I remember saying that. I remember saying that, don't forget you have to - have to cry. Of course - they
 all laughed, I - oh-I think I was - I was about then, but a very - a very young ten and very tender age ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Who came to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well there was - it wasn't - they had to go away - to Enstone, do you know Enstone? Yes, well they had to go aw
ay because - my grandfather was buried in Enstone churchyard. And - they - they went - I - we - we hadn't got a car then, we had a horse and trap. They went - some of them went in the horse and trap, and I think some of them had got their own horses and t
raps. I know there was a long retinue of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 They were all the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you wear mourning clothes for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, but my parents did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The children didn't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, the children didn't. The children never dressed 
in - in - in - had any mourning. If it - if it was a father and mother they were just dressed in white, or - some - something very simple. But - mo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 urning was only for the elderly}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  and then of course it was crepe bands you know and all long black hood things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When you went out were you taken out visiting by your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No. We never went visiting as a family. Only to my - to my relatives - away, and they were all away. No, the only - the only - if you could call it visiting, the only visiting 
we did was when we went to church you see. The services. And we were there five times on a Sunday so - we had plenty of chance of - you know, exchanging greetings and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But you went away to see relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 In the summer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But that was for holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was for holidays, on my uncles farm down in - in Nuant in Gloucestershire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you taken out shopping in Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh - no. Yes, we were taken into Oxford if my mother wanted to buy - but you see all our clothes were ma
de in Woodstock. My mother used to buy the material by the yard, and then we had a proper dressmaker, she used to measure us all up, and then make our clothes, and my sister and I were always dressed alike, and - and the boys - the boys had their things o
ut of the shop you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You did go to London with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember any other times you went with you're your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, I don't remember - except that we all went for a walk together on Sunday evenings - in the 
summer, I mean it was like an alligator, you know, two and two. But we weren't allowed to pick a flower on Sundays. No. We weren't allowed to do - and we weren't allowed to have any of the sort of songs that they sing now, we could sing hymns, and - those
 kind of things, but nothing secular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember going out on Bank Holiday outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes. Yes. Yes. We used to have picnics - in those days, you know. Well that - those were the days when my father had a car you see, and we 
used to go out into the fields, and - take our picnics out, it was very nice. And we used to go into the park. You've been in this park of course. Yes. Lovely park. Oh we've had many picnics there down by Fair Rosamund's Well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 That would be the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 hole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The whole family, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well, it would be - it would be - in the afternoon you see, perhaps he would have - an early - what we called}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 dinner, we never - didn't call it lunch, we would have an early dinner, and the
n we would go off in the afternoon, mummy would - pack baskets you see and take Thermos flasks - I don't know whether Thrmos flasks were - in vogue in those days, I don't believe they - no, we took it in bottles, and she wrapped it round with a lot of - f
lannel s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 uff. To keep it hot. We had tea in bottles.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And you took the picnic basket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, with sandwiches and things and cakes in you see. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did you do when you got there, did you play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh we played games yes, we had - oh all sorts of games, hide and seek and - all the outdoor games you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Would your father and mother play with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, oh no, they wouldn't - they'd - the only games that they'd ever play, well my mother didn't - my mother never played game
s of any sort. She wasn't a gamester, but daddy did, and we used to play draughts you see, or as I told you, we used to play - bagatelle and chess. Chess is a marvellous game, have you ever played it? I love it, do you? I've got a chess - I've got a chess
 
board here. No, the games we played really were more like - what we called tig and - you know, we used to touch each other and then you had to - if you were touched you had to run, and if you got a to a tree you put your hand on the tree, so long as your 
hand was on wood, anything wood, they couldn't touch you you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You did go away for holidays, could you tell me a bit about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, well we generally - when we went away for a holiday it was generally down on to my uncle's farm, down in Glou
cestershire. In a little place called Lambs Barn. He had a very nice farm, and - we - oh we had - wonderfully happy times there. We didn't do anything special, except that it was quite near - the Malvern Hills, we went - used to go to - into Malvern, and 
- climb up the hill you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How long did you go there for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Some - oh just about - perhaps ten days, a fortnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you go away every year or most years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, most years we went down to this farm. I can't remember going anywhere els
e but to the farm. Oh yes. We did. We went to an uncle who lived at Enstone. We used to go there sometimes for a week. They had a lovely garden. In Enstone, and they had a - a spring, a sort of - in the garden. And - oh I remember - and there was - Haytro
p
 - Haythrop Manor wasn't far away from Enstone, and I know we used to go to Haythrop sometimes, because in a cave there, wasn't it Captain Brassey who lived there? Yes, it was. And in a cave there he had a skeleton of a whale, and I remember oh we - oh we
 were intrigued with this great big skeleton.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 All the family went on holiday together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No, no, the little ones - the little ones went on their own, my lit - little brother and I, we went together, and then - the two bigger ones - stayed at home you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But did they go on holiday at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well, yes, oh yes, they used to go away for a holiday different places. You see, when my brother went away to boarding school - well when he came home, he was really glad to be at home. It was sort
 of a holiday for him, they used to - he had a bicycle you see, we all had bicycles. Which of course were - I mean it was a great thing to all go for a cycle ride. Even my mother had a bicycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You went out cycling together did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes.
 I remember going to Enstone. Yes. I suppose when I first started going to Enstone I - could only have been about seven or eight, I had a little bicycle, little tiny wheels you know, going round like this all the time. Oh it was great fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You say you didn't do anything special on the farm, did you go for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, we went for walks, and played games you see. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your uncle have children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, he had a family of children, yes. We used to play all the childish games like ta
g and all those things you know, and in the hayfield we used to sort of bury the other ones in the hayfield and - all those sort of things and of course we had - spinning tops and - and hoops, and - and skipping ropes. We had the things that children don'
t - don't have these days at all. Never hear of them do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you help in the hayfield at all while you were there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. No. No, when I was big enough to help in the hayfield I found other places to go for my holidays. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, Saturday was a preparation for Sundays. It was a preparation day. We were - allowed to go for walks, we used to go for walks, there were - there was a whole gang of us, when I was about twelve, there were a whole 
- perhaps six or eight, we would go for walks all the way round the countryside, and - we would be allowe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
 to take our tea, and we would be out - perhaps we w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 ould start directly after lunch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
 on and we - we weren't back until it was time to go to bed. We used to go through all the fields and just roam the - canals and places. We did a tremendous lot of walking in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Sunday was a special day. Sunday was the Lord's day. And we could hardly - we wouldn't dare to pick a blade of grass on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have different clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes. We had - we had - best clothes and second best clothes. When we came home from church, on a Sunday morning, we always had to change before the lunch, change into our second best cloth
es. And we wore those until it was time to go to church in the evening, and then we changed again into our best clothes. And this year's best clothes became second best the next year. Have you got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you allowed to play any games at all on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And your parents thought it was wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
We had books you see, but we had Sunday books. We were allowed to read. Well I had Sunday at Home and - and my brother had - now I've forgotten what his book was c
alled, he had a - a book that was applicable, nice stories, but all - sort of biblical you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your father read to you on a Sunday from the Bible?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes. Oh yes, we had family prayers on Sunday. Always in the evening. My father would re
ad - he would read a portion of scripture then we all had to kneel down and - turn round in the chair, and my father would pray, and - that was our Sunday evening. Then we would sing a hymn perhaps before we went to bed. In fact we used to have one or two
 of our chapel - other pupils in, sometimes on Sunday evening to sing hymns.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You said sometimes your father would play the American organ on the Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Always hymns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You said sometimes girls who worked in the shop would come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Wo
rked in the shops. If they came to - to church on a Sunday evening, then they would come over and my mother would make coffee - and sandwiches, and - I remember one girl had a violin, she used to bring it, and my father would play the American organ and w
e would all stand up and sing hymns. After the church - service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 After family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, before family prayers. That would - that ended up, the family prayers ended up the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 After the others had gone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, after the others had gone, - yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Both your parents went to the Methodist chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How often did they go on a Sunday, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Five times. Mm. Sunday school, Sunday school in the morning and afternoon, church in the morning and evenin
g, and then after the afternoon service, in church, my father used to play and I had to go to turn over for him, they had a big men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 s meeting in the Town Hall - an Evangelistic meeting, it was full of men, it was a most marvellous meeting. Every Sunday it 
was crammed full, the Town Hall in Woodstock, and my father used to play, we had a ministry you see, the preacher that preached in the morning or the evening minister, and they would go and give an address in the afternoon to the men, and I would have to 
turn over the hymn sheets for my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh yes, rather. Oh yes, we used to go in - we used to gen - generally get - there were - farm wagons, and my father used to get those you see and the horses - Mr 
Haines used to lend us his wagonette, and - well all the Sunday school children used to go, and then we used to have a tea, and then we used to have - scrambling for nuts and - sweets and - racing, little prizes for races and - oh yes, it was a highlight 
o
f the year. And then in the winter time, we had our Sunday school treat in the church when we all got up and recited, some sang, some recited, and then we had prizes - for how many times we'd attended the Sunday school during the year. Oh that was a famou
s do, the both the treat in the summer and-in the - Christmas treat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where did you go for your Sunday school treat in the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 In the summer, perhaps out to Combe, out this way, three or four miles, 'cos the horses only walked you know in the
se wagonettes, but it was marvellous. We used to dress the horses up with rosettes, and thing. And - oh it - it - oh we looked forward to the treat for weeks beforehand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did the wagons go off in procession, one or two wagons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Two - was sometimes two wagons, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And you went to a field?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
We went to a farmer's field. There were - well you see, there were lots of farmers around here that were Methodists you see, and they were only too glad to lend their fields for the - for the treat. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have to take your own dinner with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh no, no, no, no. We had - we didn't start until after lunch. After lunch you see. And then of course they - the - the people - where we were going to - gen - it was generally a Methodist
 that lent the fields, well then the lady - the - the Methodist lady would go into the - Sunday school room, which was near - the field, and they would make an urn of tea. Oh yes, we had proper - it was all done very properly. It was really sacred - in a 
way you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were there any other social activities at the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, only the - no, only just the - summer outing, and the - winter concert. Mm. Which was at Christmas you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The concert was held in the church or the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Y
es, in the - in the - no, in church. It was in the church, and we all had to recite - suitable pieces for a church you see, and some of us sang, and - then the prizes, we always had prizes in those days, for the ones who had attended over - certain number
 of times and then those who - who were under that, they - we - we had nice thick books because we'd been every time. And - the others had thinner books. All - sort of bible stories.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you belong to the chapel choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, when there was a choir, I did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did that do anything, go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do - oh - well it - yes, we used to give }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 - give - we - we - of course we}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  weren't big enough to give oratorios or - anything like the Messiah, now I have sung in the Abbot Hall with a thousand voices t
he Messiah, that was when I lived in London, and I belonged to a London church. And all the choirs in London, went to the Albert Hall and we were all dressed in white, the ladies, it was very - impressive. But - at home here - oh yes, we gave little - ora
torios like - Manager to Cross we did, and - we weren't - we weren't eloquent enough to do the Crucifi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 x}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
ion, but we did pieces from the Crucifi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 x}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
ion but not the whole thing you see. And it was a - it was - it was a - a - a - a - two manual organ my father had
, in the church, the same organ that they've got now. Daddy played it for fifty years, and I'm playing it for about thirty - thirty or forty, after he'd gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did the chapel you were in have a temperance society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh Band of Hope. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes. ON yes. I was in it. But that was at - at another church. We had to go to the other church, to what we called the United Methodist, and it was - it was - in the Olivit church, and we used to go there - I think the Band of Hope met 
once a week in the winter. Nothing in the summer but once a week in the winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did you do at Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh sang, we sang all sorts of - things you know, you mustn't touch any - mustn't ever let your - lips - touch a glass - if it's had 
beer in it. Oh no. That was very wicked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they have magic lantern shows and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes. Yes, we had magic lantern shows. In school you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was with the Band of Hope?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no. No. We did have magic lantern with
 the band of Hope, but most of the Band of Hope was singing. And signing the pledge you see and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember going on any procession in the Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. It wasn't big enough you know for that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But that was United Independent Methodist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 The Wesleyans didn't mind you going there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh no. Oh no, no. It was interchangeable you see. I mean if they had a service and we hadn't got one, we all went to them automatically. It was a very friendly affair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you belong to any clubs organised by the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. We didn't have any clubs. Not in those days, they do now but we didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was grace said in your family before meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Before every meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Who said it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well - my father generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Mum - Mummy never said it. Mummy never did anything, she was - too - you know, she was - oh, she was so quiet and so - she didn't take any part, my mother. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Oh yes. No, mummy heard us say our prayers at night, yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And you had family prayers on a Sunday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 On a Sunday, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 This is about your parents political attitudes, I don't know how much you can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
I can tell you in one sentence. My father was a Liberal, and we were all - brought up as Liberals. My mother was a Liberal, they voted Liberal, and they went to the - Liberal meetings, in the Town Hall. We - I remember the time when Mr Benne
tt, he was a Liberal and he got in for the North Oxford Division, and I remember he came down here, there was a big process - procession, and there was a pole and a big loaf on the top of a pole, and I didn't go in the procession but I watched it. I thoug
ht it was grand. And they had a big photograph - of Mr Bennett, he was the Liberal in those days you see. And he got in the North Oxford Division, we were thrilled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your father was very interested in politics then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, not very interested but he 
was a Liberal. He wouldn't - oh yes, no, we didn't attend meetings or anything, and he didn't - he never hoo-haed about it you know. If anybody asked him he said, well I'm a Liberal you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Have you any idea why he held those views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, becaus
e it was the middle course. You see, in those days there were only Liberals and Conservatives weren't there? I know the Conservative was a blue badge and we had red badges, and you see there wasn't a - there wasn't a - a - a - another party at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your father voted before 1919, you think he'd always have voted Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We didn't get a vote you see, women didn't have a vote did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your father voted Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh - always, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you know if your father ever felt himself under pressure say from his richer customers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Not to vote Liberal at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No. Oh my father - nobody would have dared to question my father. Oh you're on - you're on very soft ground. Oh no. My father had one line, and it was straight, and 
- and - he - he never deviated a scrap. But he was kind you know. He was very kind and he - had a sweet face. Wonder if I've got a photograph of him I can show you. I shouldn't t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 
hink you'll want to get anybody }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 else's news from Woodstock would you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you ever remember if your father was ever actually a member of the Liberal party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did he work for the Liberals at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. No, he just voted. Just voted, he gave his vote and he considered that was - that was the thing, that was done, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And he didn't go to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He went to meet - the meetings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 At election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes, he went to the meetings. But - and of course if anybody had asked him he would have said that he was a Li
beral you see, and - you see there were only two parties in those days, Conservatives and Liberals, and one was the high ups and the other was the intermediates you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you know if your mother - your mother was a Liberal as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 My - my - y
es, but - she was a cipher really my mother. She voted Liberal because daddy did. She didn't understand and didn't want to understand politics. It was beyond her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your father was obviously a very respected man in Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did he ever speak at elections?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When your parents were not working can you remember the sort of things they did, how they spent their spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well there wasn't much spare time. My mother had four - five children you see, and 
- although she had my aunt there wasn't much - very much spare time. My mother spent most of her spare time in walking. Now she would get up and have her breakfast, and - she would say, to my auntie what we were gong to have for lunch you see, my auntie d
i
d all the cooking - my mother went out for walks in the morning and she walked miles. My mother one day said to my brother who was then home from India, he was in India in those days, he died in Rhodesia, but he was in India, and he came over and she said
 
- she said - would you like a walk? Cecil his name was. I always called him Bunny, that was my pet name for him. He said, yes, he said, where shall we go? She said, let's go to Oxford and back. So he said, all right, all right. He said, mother you can't w
a
lk into oxford. She said, can't I? She said, you'll see. She walked into Oxford, when they got there my brother was looking a bit jaded, and he said, well now, he said, let's go to the Kadina and have a little feast up, you see, which they did, and my bro
ther said, well, he said, mother I can't walk back. Oh she said, don't be silly, she - he said, you can't walk back all that way. She said, yes, I can. She walked into Oxford, and back again. He had a taxi back. That's true.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When would that have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh - years ago now, let me see, that was when he was at home from Canada. He lived in Canada for years, and America. And then he went out to in - oh then he went to Ireland. And stayed into Ire - in Ireland for a bit, and then he went out to India, 
and he was in India twenty years. And then he was in Rhodesia for twenty years before he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So your mother went walking a lot, did she go visiting friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, my mother never visited anybody. She used to go for her walks, she used to go all 
round the countryside, long - long distances, always had her stick. And always dressed up in the morning. And - people now talk about Mrs Strong's hats that she used to wear. How smart she was. And - my other did mostly - she didn't do very much housework
 
at all, but she - made all her clothes. She used to do a lot of sewing, for the whole family, and mending. That was her chief work. My auntie did the cooking you see, and then of course the girls used to take us out you see, and - then a woman did the cle
aning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Your mother did make some clothes then or did she just mend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh she made - made them. Oh yes, she made lots of - she made nearly all our things. All our underwear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But the dresses were made by the dressmaker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well, yes, yes, in Woodstock, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But your mother made the underwear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. And one dressmaker's - name was Mrs Carsbrook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What time did your father get home from work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well he didn't go to work, - you see, the shop was in the house you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did he spend most evenings of the week at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, well they had Bible classes - over at the church. And if there was a class, what they called the class meeting, they don't have them now, but we had a class meeting then, daddy was over there you see. T
hen of course he - he - he spent a lot of time practicing the organ. As he was the organist you see, he played very well. My father would have been a Doctor of Music had he studied music instead of - having a shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So he didn't go anywhere regularly apart from the Bible Classes, he didn't have a club or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was he a temperance man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Well, no, not - not really. No. No. No, he didn't - he enjoyed a glass of beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But he didn't go out to public houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh never, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your father -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
He used to have a country round, he used to go round the country - you see. You see, that's how he first started in his business, he used to go round soliciting orders - and then he used to take them round you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And he built up the shop from that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, had a horse - a pony and trap to begin with, then of course - after a certain time of course he bought a cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was he a sporting man at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did he play games of any sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, only indoor games like - he played chess, he was very good at chess. He played chess and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember him belonging to any savings clubs, or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. He made us save.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you remember how you got on with your brothers and sisters, did you get on well with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, very well. We were a very united family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, my brother Bunny. The one that was killed. Oh no, he wasn't killed, the one that died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 He was the youngest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No, he was the eldest boy. Mm. He was away at boarding school you see, and I always had a very soft spot in my heart for him, although Arthur and I got on very nicely, as brother and sister, but I think I looked up to Bunny more than t
o - to this - the other brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 As a child who did you play with, did you play with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, we had friends of our own. I had lots of girl friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were they neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes. Well - girls at - in Woodstock you see, because I went to Oxford to school - when I was - only - twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 In Woodstock did you play with chapel families, people from the chapel or were they just sort of people who lived in the same street?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh just - just all sort - you know, people that I felt drawn to. I had lots of girl friends. They were Church of England all of them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You went to school in Oxford as a boarder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, no, as a day girl. Mm. I went in and out on the train.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But your friends remained mainly in Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Mainly, yes, well there was a very good grammar school - that was opened after I started going to Oxford - High School. There was a very good school opened here - a - a private school, to which nearly all my friends went, it was so funny. I
 daresay I should have gone there, had it not been that daddy - booked me into Oxford High - it was a very nice school I went to. Very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When you did play where did you play, in the garden or in the street or in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We were never allo
wed to play in the street. Ever. No. Used to play in the park. Just inside the park there's that hill that goes down to the lake, we used to play out on those banks. And all - all round the park we used to play, and in our own garden of course we played.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you play in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. We had a play room. Oh yes, we had a proper play room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What was that like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Very nice, we had a trapeze and - a - oh all sorts of things up there. All our games and things up there you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you play in other children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 s houses as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Not very much, no. We used to go to tea with other children, and we used to play in their gardens but not in their houses very much.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Tea was something that was very formal was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh te
a was very formal, yes. And - but - you see, they - they hadn't got a playroom like we had. They - most of them used to come to our playroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What games did you play, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh, mostly mothers and fathers and - uncles and aunts and - 
all the - the games you know that children do play. Outside of course we had hoops and we had tops and skipping ropes, we had all the things that children of that - age - had. Ye - yes, they - my parents were very lenient really, very. And we had bicycles
 
too you see. We used to go cycle rides, and then we used to do long walks, there were about six of us and we - on Saturday afternoons we had - we - we used to have our lunch and then my mother would pack up - not for all but for us, our tea, and then we u
sed to go walking all across the fields. And we used to have our tea down by the canal - oh yes, we - we - it was wonderful in those days. Children don't do things like that know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played or were you supposed to keep very clean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh no, I don't think they worried very much. My mother didn't like it if we got anything torn or anything but - they were very - lenient in those ways, very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you allowed to play with anybody you liked, children in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No, we - and we weren't really allowed to - well, when I say we played in the streets, we - we - we didn't really play in the streets, we played in the park. If we wanted to play we played in the park, or in someone's garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But could you play with anybody you liked at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No. No. They - they didn't discourage us but we just didn't - you know, we found our own - level, and - we had plenty of children that were our own - type and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You say your parents didn't like swearing, so if they thought that children -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well children didn't swear in those days. No, you never - I mean, children didn't know the words that they use today. Never heard of. In fact I some - I sometimes wonder where on earth they get the words from. - It staggers me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you belong to any youth organisations at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
We belonged to the Band of Hope. And - of course we had our own - choir practise, and church, which took up one - evening you see. And - of course when I went to Oxford school there's homework you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 It would be Band of hope one evening a week in winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes, in the winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And choir practise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. And the choir practice. Choir practice of course all the year round. And then mostly in the evenings we were
 reading or - you see we played such a lot of games, indoor games. Always in the winter - we were playing - some game - or other. Some of the games that you know I've forgotten, I couldn't play them now. But they were very interesting for children in thos
e days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
How did you spend your free time when you were at school, did you have any hobbies then? You talked a bit about your pets earlier, you had lots of pets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you collect anything or do gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well - we - the girls used 
to collect flowers and the boys used to collect butterfly - butterflies and pin them down and all that sort of thing you know. And we had crazes for collecting - perhaps one would collect acorns and then another one would collect something else. I - I rea
lly - I really forgotten what I did collect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have certain times of the year for collecting things do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well, yes. Yes, 'cos we used to collect wild flowers, I remember, I had a book of wild flowers. And then another girl would
 collect butterflies you see, and - and - and have a book of those. Oh we collected all sorts of things, leaves. Some girls would collect - leaves, and you could get very pretty leaves. And put them into a book you see, paste them into a book. Stamps we c
o
llected, I remember having a stamp album. And I'll tell you what we did have which was - which - that's never heard of today, and that was an album which you used to - get your friends to put a little - verse or something or just a little - saying, and th
en their names, at the bottom and the date when they wrote this, autograph album we called them. They're a thing of the past now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you go for walks or bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, bicycling a lot. Yes, and we had a lot of - we used - you see, we had hoo
ps in those days, we bowled hoops and - used to go out in the country, and we went - there were a collection of children - the gentleman across the road, his daughter and son - we - we - there were about eight of us, we used to do - circular walks - all r
ound the country lanes, and take packed lunches, that sort of thing, thermos flasks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you do that with other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Or your parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, not - never with our parents. Always a gang of children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you take part in any sports at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, I played tennis. And - well of course as I told you we had a full - a full bagatelle board, indoor sport you see and home. The - the walking was our}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 main sport, we used to go these long rambles - in the country la}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 es all th
e way round you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you go to any theatres or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Concerts, but my father didn't like us to go to the theatre, he thought it was - you know, not quite right for children. I don't think I went to a theatre until I was about - until I was about fifteen. 'Til I was going in to Oxford to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about - was there a cinema in Oxford before you went to school or when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes, there was a cinema - we also had a cinema here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Ye
s. Yes, but that was only on Saturday evenings. And it was sixpence. The - the fee to go in was sixpence and I remember on one occasion - the film caught fire, and we - oh it was a terrific - of course it was great fun for the children, it was a - almost 
a children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
s cinema you see, but a few older people went, and there was one old lady went who was a cripple, and she was - she had crutches you see, under the arm crutches, and her name was Mrs Gardner, well now she could never move without these crutches b
ut when there was a fire nobody will ever now how she got out of the hall, but she got out and the crutches were left behind, which was very amusing to the children you can imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your parents give you pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. Now my father used to have occasional travel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
ers. One was a very very - not opulent, but he - he was - richer than the rest, and he always used to give us half a crown, and my father promised - that when we got a pound - of course we - we dealt in farthings you see and h
a'pennies, we got a lot of sweets for a farthing, in fact if I had a penny I used to have four packets, big packets of sweets for a penny, and - there were some very good sweetshops in Woodstock, and - now what was I going to tell you about this - this mo
ney, oh yes, when the travel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
er came, this particular man always gave us half a crown you see. Used to come about twice a year. And my father said, now, he said, when you get up to a pound then I will give you five pounds, and you can go to the bank and you
 can open an account with the bank, and you can put six pounds - Post Office savings bank, you had - you licked stamps you know and put them on a form. And - ohn I - I - oh I strove, I - I saved every bit I could - manage until I got a pound and then as I
 say five pounds went in and - and oh I thought I was immensely rich when I had five pounds. 'Course that was a tremendous lot of money.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You said you used to have pennies and ha'pennies when you went to Woodstock Fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, we had tuppence. Yes,
 we saved up all the year for Woodstock Fair, and we always had four ha'pennies, which was tuppence. Now we spent those individually and very often we - we - we sometimes had the farthings as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Where would that money come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Odd ha'pennie
s or pennies that we got from various people. I - would - but as such we never had pocket money, like the children today. Oh my word, what a difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house or family? This is not people
 paid but just generally, relatives or friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. No, the people that we had - we had a washerwoman, and a cleaning woman and they were paid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Then my aunt looked after everything. We had my aunt living, I told you, with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 This would also happen when the younger members of your family were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm. Mm. Yes, well you had a district nurse, and my aunt was the housekeepers then. With these other
 - people. We didn't have a living in maid until I was quite sort of grown up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. Well - my father had a brother living at Enstone. And - but of course Enstone was a very long way off, you know
, we used to cycle there, I had a bicycle and we used to cycle to Enstone and that was a real - day's - you know effort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How much did you see of them then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well about once a year we went - we used to go to Enstone about once a year. To visit my
 uncle, sometimes I would stay - a few days, you know, there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No, my father - was never - he - you see, they were always so busy and we always had such a lot of company ourselves in the home, you see there are 
four children - and then as I told you the nursemaid and - the other various women who came in to work, to clean and do the washing and do the ironing - so that we always had plenty - there was plenty of life in the home. And of course we had school}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 friends, I told you - we used to go walks and play - play around you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your mother have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were friends of your parents, or people your parents knew, ever invited into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, and on Sunday ev
enings - did I not tell you that? Yes. Yes. Well, no, we didn't have many friends in the house. It's - a - apart from the church people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So that would be Sunday evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were there any other particular days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did people call by casually without invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. Unless they had some - some specific business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Its' often said that people in those days made their own amusements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What do you think your parents did when they got together with their f
riends if they did apart from the Sunday evening, or with their family, did they make -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well they - I mean to say - they - they didn't have time. You see, and my father was the organist at the church, and most of my father's time was spent practicin
g the organ. And mummy spent the time with us, reading to us or - you see, and then of course we had my aunt ass well, you see, so that really it - it was a sort of family - we played - we played ludo and snakes and ladders, and my father taught us to pla
y chess, which we loved.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  All of us, we all took to ches}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 s.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Many people divide society into classes or groups.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 In the time before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one class or to one group or another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you mean people that - that we called the upper ten? Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Can you tell me how it worked in Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes. Well, in Woodstock - the trades}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 people were always friendly to each other. And the professional people, always held themselves a little aloof - from the trades}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 people. And specially }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  trades}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
people that were uneducated. A lot of people in those days you see were not educated at all, they were just - homely nice people you know, but - if - if a person was - was well educated, and a trades person of course you had the entr\'e9
e into - what we call the professional people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Who were the upper ten you talked about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well the upper ten was the Duke of Marlborough, and - titled people - Lord Dillon and people like that, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 They mixed with nobody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well - they - well they had their own - yes, they - they - they were more class - there was much class distinction in those days than there is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Then there would be the professional people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. There - there were
 what I call the upper ten, then there were professional people, then there were the - the higher business people, like we were, you see, well and then there were working class people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What sort of people belonged to the higher business people, the higher trades people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well, people like ourselves and the Brandenbury family. You see, people who were - educated sufficiently enough to take office as Mayor of the town and Aldermen and those sort of offices.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What sort of people would you have said belonged to the professional classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well - well people like lawyers and doctors. They were the professional people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 And the working class were - were - well they were the working class you see, the lower order 
people without education, the just - just good people you know, nice people but - but - working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember being brought}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 up to treat people of different classes any differently from one another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No, my father - no, my father was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 hristian, and he said, if you are a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
hristian - we were all God's people and they were - everybody, whatever they did, they were very dear to God.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you ever told to curtsey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no. Oh no. I wouldn't I - no, I don't think I would have done tha
t. I was that proud I wouldn't have - I wouldn't have curtsied to anybody. We were very deferential - to people, to my doctor you see. But the doctor used to come and - and sit down and have a chat and - chat all about anything but your health and then it
 would gradually veer round to one's health you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you ever told to call anybody sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No. No. No. We didn't - we - we didn't believe in that kind of thing. No I believe if you could get the right sort of people in Woodstock you'll get quite a lot of that out of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember anybody behaving in that way to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Calling your father sir or your mother madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, the boy - yard boy, we had - I forgot to tell you we had a horse didn't I? D
id I tell you? Yes, we had a yard boy. Oh he always called my father sir and - touched his cap you know, when he came in the morning and when he went away at night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Obviously the most important people in Woodstock were the upper ten as you call them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well there were so few of them, as you can imagine. I mean they were - they were - there were - there were - heaps and heaps of the lower order. Then of course - of our type of people, there were - there were quite nice families, distinguished famil
ies who - who were a cut above the - the other people. And - and then of course there were the professional people that we - oh we thought the world of the doctor. He - he was so kindly, you see, and he never made any difference, he always - we - he ch}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 ate
d to us, just like I'm chatting to you know you see, used to come in the home, very nice. Of course if we didn't - if - if he wasn't nice well we didn't have him because - we paid in those days. You see? So that we could distinguish with whom we should ha
ve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you come in contact at all with any of the upper ten in any way at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well - no, not the - not the real upp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 er ten. Oh no, they were quite}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 aloof}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Who would the clergymen associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well they're always the - they're not the upper ten, they're the professional people, the clergymen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Schoolteachers? Well they were all - were all so friendly - together. We - we - we didn't - I mean, they were our teachers and we respected them, but they were no different class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about the farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh well the farmers were class on their own. My brother grew up to be a farmer so - I was very conversant with the farmers - there was a big}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 ball in the - in the Bear, a farm - there was a special farmers ball in the Bear which was absolutely a - a - a noted occasion in Woodstock, the farmers ball.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they mix with the trades}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 people at all socially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Yes. It did - but it depended what - you see there were classes of farmers, there was th
e - smallholder, and then you got the - you got the - the smallholder who was very - well on the edge of farming sort of, he had a few acres you see. Well then there was the intermediate one. And then there were the big farmers, the landowners.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What sort of people do you think went to church, to the Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh - all the - we looked up to the Church of England people really. The chapel people were considered a lower order. Because - it was the professional people. Of course a lot of th
e ordinary people went to church, I don't think one could distinguish, but of course we did think it was rather grand to go to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did all the people in the working class where you lived have the same standard of living or would you say there were
 different groups within the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
I should say there were - there were - there was a difference. Yes, you - you could - you could put it into two groups really. The very poor working class. You know, lived on about twelve bob a week, that c
lass. And then the better - still working - but earning more money, there - I should say two classes of working class people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Could you describe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  a family in each group, roughl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 y what they'd be like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I - I wouldn't know, 'cos I never mixed with them you see. Sorry, that's - right out of my province.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did one of the groups feel themselves superior to the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes, and they weren't allowed to play, the - the - better class group weren't - weren't allowed to mix with the others
 because you see a lot of them were not very clean, in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 So some families then were thought of as rough and some as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm. Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was this very much a correspondence between Old Woodstock and New Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Y
es. There were one or two - oh yes, we didn't - we didn't think much of Old Woodstock people, except the farming class. And - there were a few - you see - a lot of the old - old - Old Woodstock people were glovers. It was a gloving class of people up ther
e
. And a lot of them did gloving at home. They used to go to the factory and get the gloves, and then, you know, go - go home and - and - and machine them up. That sort of thing. But - I - I - I really don't know a lot about Old Woodstock, because we didn'
t - we used to pass through, but I didn't go up there to visit anybody.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember any sort of distinction between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No, I think they were considered, you know - fifty- fifty. Unless of course that was a very note
d craftsmen, the - you know, the people that were really genius - and then of course there was a difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you think your mother and father had the same attitude to people in different classes and groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Very - in a very minor degree, only
 a minor degree. My mother didn't like us mixing with rough children. But apart from that if they weren't rough - and - and - had bad habits, then we were allowed really to go - to mix with anybody. My mother said - my mother said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 hristians should be - be able to mix with anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a distinct social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 In a way, yes. My mother was a bit proud you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Why do you think she felt this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Well, because I think you see she'd alwa
ys mixed with gentle people. I mean she wasn't in - in - in - well - call it what you will, service you see, I mean they were very modest houses, and they didn't do the sort of menial work that ordinary servants did at all. And - she - she was with titled
 people my mother. What she did I - I don't - really don't know. But I only knew that she was very - my mother was a gentle woman, she used to say to me, I hate the word lady. Oh I hated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 
 and despise the word lady, gen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 tlewoman, yes. Yes, I like the word gent
lewoman. And my mother was a gentle woman. My mother had nor coarse - coarse - well I mean she was so refined and my father too. My father, I told you, went to Palestine did I? For six weeks. Yes, and we were - oh we were thrilled when we had a cable from
 
him. They had a cable, they - they had a code between them. Several words meant a long sentence of things, to save the money you see. 'Cos of course it was very costly. My father was only - the second man - he was the first man in Woodstock to leave Woods
t
ock to go abroad. There was another - Layden who went to Palestine I think a week or two before daddy, but daddy was the first one in Woodstock. And the people that came round, to see the trophies he brought back, David's sling you know, the sling he slun
g
 the Goliath with and - all those sort of things you know. Oh the trophies that he brought back. And of course we got very tired - after all he'd had about six weeks of people coming to the door to see Mr Strong to tak about Palestine because of course it
 was a very long trip he did, he made, and he did the thing thoroughly. I've got a photograph of him somewhere, taken as a Bedouin Shelk, in Jerusalem on Christmas Day. So it was very - I mean, we had a lot of interest in our lives as children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was it possible at that time do you think to move from one class or group to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well it depends what you were doing. Oh yes, you could easily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How was it done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well - I mean, supposing you were - supposing you - you did - what shall we say
 - well just roughly speaking - supposing - I - I hadn't a horse you see, and - people wh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
'd got horses you see were - were in a different class altogether. Well now supposing I had a horse, which I did, then I could go riding with other people you see. Th
at kind of thing. Created - and if you moved, you see, I mean, I - my father had to give no end of account of all the relatives and what he did, I was one of the first lady clerks in the bank ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember anybody being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. But chiefly because of behaviour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 It was a natural thing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, yes, absolutely a natural thing that was. In my day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, we had lots of policemen in those days, we haven't got them now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did you think of him, did your mother say, I'll call the policeman, if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. I never - I never remember her saying that, no. No, my mother was the most gentle
 - I never remember my mother hitting me except once, and that was when I was down on a - a farm, an uncles farm, and the cousin that was there annoyed me, and I - I - I boxed her ears or did something, and then - my mother hit me. But that's the only tim
e in my life - did my mother ever - and then she was so - sad that she'd done it, she went out and bought me sponge cakes for tea. I - you know that's an isolated case. Both from the point of punishment and then re}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 cinding you see and - and - being sad - sad about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
This is probably in Old Woodstock, if there was anybody there who was strongly disapproved of, how would they show it, how would the community show it, have you any idea?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You've never heard of anything called rough music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were you ever given lessons by one of your parents or a tutor or a governess when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What school was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was to the Woodstock - Council School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When you first started what time in the morning did you go and come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Went at nine - oh when I first started, went at nine and finished - oh no, I didn't, no, I went the full time I think when I first started. But it'
s such a long long time ago. You imagine going back seventy - seventy-five years. I'll tell you what I can - what - what I think is true and I can remember. I remember that we played with beads - to begin with, and picture books. And we went to school and
 
there was a sort of gallery with - there was a big high - gallery in one of the windows, a very big window, and - I sat on a - form, there were forms with no backs do you see, rows of forms the little children sat on, and I went up this. And - oh I was ev
e
r so proud when I went to school, I thought it was grand. And - oh I enjoyed being with the other children very much. Well then when I got a bit bigger, when I got we'll say to the age of eight, then - I was put in charge of a class of the babies, when I 
w
as about eight, and I used to thread their beads for them and - and help. Help - I used to help the teacher when I was about eight. I went to that school until I was twelve. And - then by the time I was twelve of course I was in the upper classes you see,
 
with - a - a Miss - the - the governess's - the governess name was - the one who taught me was called Miss Davis, there were two Miss Davis's, one in the infant school and one in the upper school, and then our head - headmistress was called Miss Walker. N
ow Miss Walker was very - she was a very educated woman, cap and gown woman - in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Then you went to school after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Then I went into Oxford to school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How did you get into Oxford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well - when - to bet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 in - first of all - I went by train. I went by train. And then - when the buses started - I finished school by bus.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What sort of school was that, that was a private school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, private school where my father paid, and - every lesson was - was - it was a very ex
pensive school and - every lesson was - was - a - an extra. Even - even drill. We had a proper - Ser - Sergeant Major - from - from - from the Army who was paid to come and teach us drill, and it was a - it was a beautiful school and as I say the governes
ses were nearly all cap and gown-people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 At Woodstock board school, the first school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 First school, the national school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You came home for your meals then did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did you think of Woodstock school, did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, I loved it. Mm. Oh I loved it because I thought I was being educated. You see, and I thought that was a grand thing to be educated. Oh yes, and my father - my father was very - very - keen on education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you like the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, very much. Yes. I was very happy there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did the teachers at Woodstock emphasise certain things as important in life, manners or tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes. Curriculum was quite a - a thing, even in the - more than it is in - it is now, it is
n't at all now, they don't care what you do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about ways of speaking, did they speak you that at the first school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Grammar? Oh yes, in - in - but then I - I mean I heard that at home you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about punishment at the first school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I never had any punishment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did anybody, was anybody ever punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, they used to have the cane. Hold out their hand you know and have a little - if they were very small of course they didn't cane them, but when you got to the bigger school, oh yes, you - you had the cane. I never had the cane though, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Was it the same for girls as boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well the boys school I don't know because it - after we were infants we were separated, there was a boys school and a girls school you 
see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But the girls were caned in your bit of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes, yes, we - oh yes, we were questioned quite - intelligently you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about visiting the school or did they meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No, but - you see, the teachers really were - well they were friends of ours. So that we could go home and say you see, and - and I revered Miss Davis, I mea
n she was very - she was very - Miss Fanny Davis was - oh she was the cats whishers to me. And Miss Walker of course, she was almost irreproachable, Miss Walker. Oh yes, because she could speak German, and if you could speak German I mean you were well up
 on the people like I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did the children at Woodstock come from a similar type of homes to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Well the people that I - I mixed with - did. Of course there were poorer people you see. Only we all had the same education. But I'm afraid a lot of people didn't make the same use - that we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did the teachers single out some children for special treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No. Oh no. We all had the same treatment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were there gangs or groups at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes. Yes, we - you see, y
ou had your own specific friends, well then when you went out - into the playroom you see - you were with your group. We - we - we never mixed with what were called the - underlings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were there any children that were actually left out of things do you think? Out of groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No, I shouldn't think so. What I can remember. I mean there were those - there were the - what we called the - the lower order of people like the Old Woodstock people and people that were - well they weren't very clean a lot of
 them you know, weren't at all clean. Well we were kept well away from them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 When you went to Oxford, you had your meal at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What did you have to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 We didn't have a school meal. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You took it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes, we took - I took sandwiches. Mm. And I had a hot meal when I got back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you like that school as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh I adored it. I adored that school, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you still feel the same about the teachers there as you did at Woodstock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no. Oh
 no. The whole thing you see was a lift up, can you understand what I mean when I say a lift up? I mean you see, always - I'm afraid I - I was born with a sort of - I can't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 ell you, it's something in me you know. I think you've come to the wrong person in coming to me actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I don't know. You think it's all right? What you want? The material you need? All right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about the sort of things they taught you at Oxford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh we - we taught - were taught everything, German, French, everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they teach you to speak well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you have elocution?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
No, I didn't have elocution as such, but my goodness no. I mean - I don't think - you see, we spoke correctly at home, therefore there was no need to - my father and mother spoke very correctly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about punishment at Oxford, was there any punishment there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well you had an - you had an order mark - for a very slight offence. But if it was a grave offence then you had a conduct mark. And 
I think I only had one all the time I was at that school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about the children at Oxford, were they from very much the same sort of homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes. Yes. The people that I - the people that I liked, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did they come from the country around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Oh yes, the villages and the country around, lots of them were farmers daughters and - and really well educated - professional peoples daughters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Were there any gangs or groups at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. Well - not like ther
e were - not the same type of gang because they were - they weren't those type of people you see. Socially - when I went to school - at Oxford, we were socially - equal, all equal you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Fifteen and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Would you have stayed any longer if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you attend any part time education afterwards? Evening classes or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I would have loved to have gone to university.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But you do think you benefited from -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But - oh yes, I - oh I benefited from my school in Oxford very greatly. In every way. In every way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 While you were at school did you have any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I'd like to talk about your first full time job, which is the one you kept wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Mm. I was in the bank for - I did a little job - of work - learning millinery, baby's millinery, make little hats you see. I did that job. But it was a very
 - I had to provide everything, thimbles and everything. And I don't think - do you know, I cannot remember whether I was paid for that job. I don't think I was paid, but - if I was paid it was only about half a crown a week or something like that. But -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was when you first left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That was when I first left school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 How did you get that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Well they came after me, because I think they thought that I was the type of person they wanted, and - as I say - it was - it was al
most practicing you see. I used to do the little baby's hats - with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 rushed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
 ribbon, all the pretty little things you see. And then of course I - I felt that that wasn't my niche in life at all, that I must - plunge out you see. Well then - my father - wrote
 - up to the - what then was the London and Provincial Bank. And when I was - I think I was about sixteen when I went away - I went to Camberley in Surrey, I got a job there, and - my - my stipend was - eighteen shillings a week, out of which I had to pay
 
fifteen shillings - for digs, which only left me three shillings - for clothes, fares - everything, amusements, everything. But my father - always paid - my railway fares home. My mother supplied me with clothes. And - the - the three shillings really was
 
- for stamps and pocket money and mummy often would send me stamps in a - in a - a letter. Now I was in that bank, I was one of the first - there were only two lady clerks in the whole of that bank, I was one and another one - another lady called Miss Fre
e
r, she's very nice lady, and I'd only been in the bank three months before I was put on a counter. I did counter work in the lunch hour, when the manager was upstairs. Now the manager was - oh he was - he was out of the top drawer, that manager, very nice
 
people, and he married a lady who'd been presented at court, and her father was - a Major in the Militia. Now they had - they lived in the Action Estate, which was a magnificent place. When you got to the door, I went there several times for tea, and so o
n
, there was a footman there to invite you in and - servants to wait on you, and of course that was just in my - up my street. I adored every minute. I was in that bank for - three years. And then I said to my father, he came to see me once, and - I said, 
d
addy, I would like to get back to Oxford. And he said, would you? And I said, yes, I would daddy. And be at home. I said, perhaps I could have a motor bike, you see, and go in and out to Oxford. This was all in my little mind. So my father said, well - he
 
said, he said, I could contact Sir Edward Holden, I know him very well, and he was the chairman then of the Midland Bank in Oxford. So daddy contacted Sir Edward Holden, and he wrote to the managers at Oxford at the Midland Bank, Oxford, who's name was Mr
 
Gevan, oh such a nice gentleman, a real top notcher you know, real bank manager in those days, you - anybody can be a bank manager now. But you had to be somebody to be a bank manager in those days, well - they - I had a notification that I was to - I was
 
to present myself at the Midland Bank on such and such a day at nine o'clock on the morning, which I did. And - I was shown into the manager's room and he said, you are Miss Strong? And I said, yes. He said, well, he said, we've got a - an - we've got a l
e
tter from Sir Edward Holden, saying that we have to make room for a new clerk, and you are the new clerk, a Miss Strong of Woodstock. And - I - I said, yes, that is true. I said, my father knew Sir Edward Holden very well, and he promised that - he would 
g
et me in here so that I could live at home. Is this all going down - of interest? Oh good. Anyhow - he said, well Miss Strong, he said, I don't know what we're going to give you to do because we're fully staffed. Well I said, I don't mind anything. Well h
e said, would you be prepared to work, on a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247013\charrsid15815407 ledger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
? I said, anything, yes, I'd love to work on a ledger, because I'd done everything in the other bank, as I tell you I was even on a counter. I'd only been there three months when they gave me a till, I had a
 relief till in the luncheon hour, to get me used to everything. I did a bit of everything except interviewing clients you see. So anyway - I was at Oxford branch for five years, very happy. But very hard work compared with Camberley. And of course I - I 
w
as practically engaged to a boy at Sandhurst, in those days, he was the nephew of Sir William Markham, he was called Harold Markham, and he - oh he - he was very kind to me, he had a - a - a red Indian motorbike and I used to come home on that motorbike y
o
u know, backwards and forwards for - vacations you see, and he proposed that we should elope and go to Canada and marry. But I couldn't see myself doing that. After all my parents had done for me. I thought, no, I can't go - go and leave them, and marry, 
so - that fizzled out you see, I was terribly upset about it because - I really was in love with that boy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You went on working in the bank after the war?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 I was in the Midland bank for five years doing everything - on the counter and - and doing
 - all the jobs, working ledgers and everything. Well I became - rather ill, and I had two operations in three months during which time my strength was very depleted and I felt really worn out. And - though at that time they were weeding out all the clerk
s
 that had had - over a certain amount of sick leave. For - not forgetting that Sir Edward Holden had got me into the bank - I had my - my - they said - you see - they would give me three months salary, and that they wouldn't require my services any longer
.
 So, I thought, well I don't mind, I don't mind. So - I - I waited a bit and then I said to my father, I said, daddy, I think I'd like to run a poultry farm. And he said, would you? My brother was farming out here, he had a very nice small - farm, it was 
o
nly - it was only two hundred acres, but a very nice farm, and I negotiated with my brother and he allowed me to - to rent - half a big field. Oh and I had a marvellous poultry farm out there. Well of course I had that for a couple of years, and I was fig
h
ting fit because I used to cycle from here, over to my brother's farm, I - and my brother built me a little hut, at which I had a little stove in and I used to make a cup of cocoa at eleven in the morning, and - well - Bob's your uncle, I was - I was awfu
l
ly - awfully fit, and I started off with a collection of Light Sussex - chicken. Well then I got on to Silver Dust Winged Leghorns, and then I had a few ducks, Khaki Campbells and Indian Runners, and I had quite a little holding over there. And I did quit
e
 well, but the trouble with a small farm like that, unless you've got about - two hundred or three hundred head of birds - you - you need that amount to make a real living. And I was sort of spending the money that I had saved whilst I was in the Midland 
B
ank. I was - that was going gradually. And - so in the end I - decided that I would sell the farm, and I went to the bank manager at the National Provincial bank in Woodstock - he was a friend of ours and I said to him, Dick, do you think there's any chan
c
e of my getting back to the bank? And he said, well no, I don't I - he - he said, because we're not taking any more lady clerks. He said, we're - you know, we're just taking - taking men. And - so I said, well - I said, you see, I - I - I've had eight yea
r
s experience because - I'd done five years in the Midland and three in the London Provincial, and I said, I think I should be valuable to somebody. So I got a friend living in London, she was a schoolmistress, and I wrote to here and I said, can I come up
 
to you for the weekend? And she said yes, of course you can. Well when I got there I said, I'm going to negotiate with a bank about getting into a bank again. I'll make this short I think now. And - the long - and short of it was that I went to see the ma
n
ager of the of Barclays Bank at Head Office in Lombard Street, and he didn't know I was coming, and I got in touch with a messenger at the door and said, could you tell me the name of the staff manager? And he said, yes, he gave me the name of this man an
d
 I said well, I wonder if you would ask him if he could get - have an interview with a Miss Strong from Woodstock. And he did and the - the - the - staff manager said yes, he would see me - at two o'clock. So I went out and had a nice lunch, I dressed mys
e
lf up like a cats - body, no - no - you know, no business, and - I went in you see and - I knocked on the door and he said, come in. And I said, you - you are Mr so and so. Having ascertained the name from the messenger. And he said, yes. And he said, I u
n
derstand you're Miss Strong, Woodstock, and - I said, yes. He said, well what is your business Miss Strong. Well, I said, I am going to offer myself as a clerk in your - in your bank. So, he said, well he said, we're not taking lady clerks now. And I said
,
 no, I know, but I said, you see I can give you eight years experience, banking experience, of - of most of the - of the jobs in the bank. He said, well what have you done? I told him. Well, he said, of course that's rather different. He said, well Miss S
t
rong, he said, I'm very - I - I'm very - pleased that you came, and he said, I can't - appoint you - to a branch because, he said, your name must go before the board of directors in their meeting on Friday. This was on a Monday. So I thanked him very much
 
and was shown out and I went home - and - I came home from London to my mother, and I said, mummy. She said, do you think you've got that job? I said, I'm confident I have. If the - if the board of directors, you know, will - grant - grant me the job, and
 
so I was going to stay with some friends at Yately for the weekend, before going I said to my mother, now look mummy, I said, if there's a telegram comes, a telegram for me - of any sort, open it and - telephone me - to Camberley, where I was going - back
 
to the old place where I'd made friends, you see, my first job. So - on the - Saturday morning, this was on the Friday, on the Saturday morning, I had - a - a telegram from my mother, report West Brompton Branch, Monday, that was the next Monday, of cours
e
 I had to rush home - get everything ready, I just took enough to - in a small case you see, had my luggage sent on and I was in Baraclays bank for twenty years. Did everything nearly in the bank. My last job in the bank - and I would still have been ther
e
 longer than that, only - my - my mother became senile and needed looking after. And at that time we had - my father owned five houses here, and my mother said, well now, Gwen is giving up her job to come and take care of us, and I think we should give he
re a house. My father - asked which one I'd like and I chose this one and here I am. That's the end of my story.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 But only for a short time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did starting full time work change your relationship do you think with your parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Or with your brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 No. I taught in the Sunday school, and - I attended - services both morning an
d evening. Mrs Morgan'll fill in what I haven't said. Bless here heart, I - I visit her you know, did she tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you take any interest in politics after you'd started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 None whatsoever. Except that I was a Liberal and I've always been a Liberal and shall always be one. Why I've no idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Do you think it was because of your father that you were a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Yes. Mm. It's - I believe in the middle - middle course of everything, and the Liberals given a chance now I think would - 
if we get enough - votes - recorded - I think - I think the Liberals have got a policy now which would probably pull this world round. This country round rather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 You told me earlier how you spent your spare time before you left school, did you continu
e to spend your spare time in the same way, say when you went to Camberley and then came back to Oxford for a bit at the Midland Bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm. Mm. Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 That would take us up to 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Did you continue to do much the same sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 
Yes, I - I had music lessons, I had a - a tutor who come home - over, a music master, who came over for - from Wootton, and taught me music. There was one period of my time, before I left Woodstock at all, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3477774\charrsid15815407 when we - we had a sort of piero}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 t troup
e and we went out - we had an old horse and - well it was a wagonette thing, we used to go out in, and I used to sing a bit and the others - they were just - a group of us from Woodstock, went out having - giving concerts in the villages. That might inter
est - be of interest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15212217 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 What about in Camberley, what did you do there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1967143 GS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13967328\charrsid15815407 Oh no, nothing there. No, I was fully occupied with - with the cadet that I should have married - when I was in Camberley.
